{"type":"message","id":"30945502","parentId":"0529dac1","timestamp":"2026-03-30T22:01:58.332Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Tue 2026-03-31 00:01 GMT+2] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: Analysiere pyproject.toml aus karpathy/autoresearch auf ABHÄNGIGKEITSRISIKEN:\n\n```toml\n[project]\nname = \"autoresearch\"\nversion = \"0.1.0\"\ndescription = \"Autonomous pretraining research swarm\"\nreadme = \"README.md\"\nrequires-python = \">=3.10\"\ndependencies = [\n    \"kernels>=0.11.7\",\n    \"matplotlib>=3.10.8\",\n    \"numpy>=2.2.6\",\n    \"pandas>=2.3.3\",\n    \"pyarrow>=21.0.0\",\n    \"requests>=2.32.0\",\n    \"rustbpe>=0.1.0\",\n    \"tiktoken>=0.11.0\",\n    \"torch==2.9.1\",\n]\n\n[tool.uv.sources]\ntorch = [\n    { index = \"pytorch-cu128\" },\n]\n\n[[tool.uv.index]]\nname = \"pytorch-cu128\"\nurl = \"https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu128\"\nexplicit = true\n```\n\nPrüfe:\n1. Welche Dependencies könnten Sicherheitsrisiken haben?\n2. Sind die Versionen gepinnt oder flexible?\n3. Welche externen Indexe werden verwendet?\n4. Welche Dependencies sind unkritisch, welche kritisch?\n\nGib Empfehlungen für Versions-Pinning und Security-Updates."}],"timestamp":1774908118330}}
{"type":"message","id":"cb6cfa71","parentId":"30945502","timestamp":"2026-03-30T22:02:23.011Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":" Der Benutzer möchte eine Analyse der Abhängigkeiten in einem pyproject.toml durchführen. Ich werde die Datei analysieren und nach Sicherheitsrisiken suchen. Lassen Sie mich die verschiedenen Aspekte durchgehen:\n\n1. Sicherheitsrisiken bei Dependencies\n2. Version Pinning vs flexible Versionen\n3. Externe Indexe\n4. Kritische vs unkritische Dependencies\n\nIch werde auch nach bekannten Sicherheitslücken in diesen Paketen suchen.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"text","text":" Ich analysiere das pyproject.toml auf Abhängigkeitsrisiken. Zunächst suche ich nach aktuellen Sicherheitsinformationen zu den verwendeten Paketen."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tool_CwRnZ61zOCGe0Z9tMSsjoB48","name":"web_search","arguments":{"query":": true,"}},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tool_S79izp7rPZOQfEpCX686EpNp","name":"web_search","arguments":{"query":"pytorch 2.9.1 security vulnerabilities CVE"}},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tool_7Alrl1Ta3EoFN0q1UEi5yj9f","name":"web_search","arguments":{"query":"requests 2.32.0 security vulnerabilities"}},{"type":"text","text":"  "}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"kimi-coding","model":"kimi-k2-thinking","usage":{"input":7422,"output":205,"cacheRead":960,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":8587,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774908118332}}
{"type":"message","id":"073c5e23","parentId":"cb6cfa71","timestamp":"2026-03-30T22:02:24.204Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"tool_CwRnZ61zOCGe0Z9tMSsjoB48","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \": true,\",\n  \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n  \"model\": \"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n  \"tookMs\": 1172,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"content\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"1462405e7303a87b\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nI'm sorry, your request seems to be incomplete. Could you please provide more information or clarify what you need assistance with?\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"1462405e7303a87b\\\">>>\",\n  \"citations\": []\n}"}],"details":{"query":": true,","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash","tookMs":1172,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"gemini","wrapped":true},"content":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"1462405e7303a87b\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nI'm sorry, your request seems to be incomplete. Could you please provide more information or clarify what you need assistance with?\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"1462405e7303a87b\">>>","citations":[]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774908144201}}
{"type":"message","id":"4c03ccb9","parentId":"073c5e23","timestamp":"2026-03-30T22:02:31.732Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"tool_S79izp7rPZOQfEpCX686EpNp","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"pytorch 2.9.1 security vulnerabilities CVE\",\n  \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n  \"model\": \"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n  \"tookMs\": 8696,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"content\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"06275e7a7e88d399\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nPyTorch version 2.9.1 is affected by a critical security vulnerability identified as **CVE-2026-24747**. This vulnerability, with a CVSS v3 score of 9.8, allows attackers to execute arbitrary code through malicious model files.\\n\\nThe core issue lies within PyTorch's checkpoint loading mechanism, specifically in the `weights_only` unpickler. It fails to properly validate pickle opcodes and storage metadata when processing `.pth` checkpoint files. This allows attackers to craft malicious files that can exploit weaknesses in the unpickler, leading to heap memory corruption and potentially remote code execution with the same privileges as the victim's process. The attack vector is considered network-based with low complexity, making it relatively straightforward to exploit through compromised repositories or distributed malicious models.\\n\\nTo mitigate this risk, users are strongly advised to upgrade immediately to PyTorch version 2.10.0 or newer, as the development team has addressed the issue in these versions by implementing proper validation of pickle opcodes and storage metadata. Until an upgrade is possible, extreme caution should be exercised when loading checkpoint files from untrusted sources.\\n\\nOther vulnerabilities mentioned in relation to the `torch` package in general, or earlier versions, include:\\n*   Deserialization of Untrusted Data via the `load_state_dict()` function.\\n*   Integer Overflow or Wraparound.\\n*   Out-of-bounds Write vulnerabilities in functions like `torch.jit.jit_module_from_flatbuffer`, when using `@torch.jit.script`, and through `torch.lstm_cell`.\\n*   Buffer Overflow issues in functions like `unpack_sequence` and `pad_packed_sequence`.\\n*   Improper Resource Shutdown or Release through `torch.cuda.nccl.reduce`.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"06275e7a7e88d399\\\">>>\",\n  \"citations\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://cyberpress.org/pytorch-vulnerability-allows-memory-corruption-leading-to-remote-code-execution/\",\n      \"title\": \"cyberpress.org\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://security.snyk.io/package/pip/torch/2.9.1\",\n      \"title\": \"snyk.io\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://security.snyk.io/package/pip/torch\",\n      \"title\": \"snyk.io\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"pytorch 2.9.1 security vulnerabilities CVE","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash","tookMs":8696,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"gemini","wrapped":true},"content":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"06275e7a7e88d399\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nPyTorch version 2.9.1 is affected by a critical security vulnerability identified as **CVE-2026-24747**. This vulnerability, with a CVSS v3 score of 9.8, allows attackers to execute arbitrary code through malicious model files.\n\nThe core issue lies within PyTorch's checkpoint loading mechanism, specifically in the `weights_only` unpickler. It fails to properly validate pickle opcodes and storage metadata when processing `.pth` checkpoint files. This allows attackers to craft malicious files that can exploit weaknesses in the unpickler, leading to heap memory corruption and potentially remote code execution with the same privileges as the victim's process. The attack vector is considered network-based with low complexity, making it relatively straightforward to exploit through compromised repositories or distributed malicious models.\n\nTo mitigate this risk, users are strongly advised to upgrade immediately to PyTorch version 2.10.0 or newer, as the development team has addressed the issue in these versions by implementing proper validation of pickle opcodes and storage metadata. Until an upgrade is possible, extreme caution should be exercised when loading checkpoint files from untrusted sources.\n\nOther vulnerabilities mentioned in relation to the `torch` package in general, or earlier versions, include:\n*   Deserialization of Untrusted Data via the `load_state_dict()` function.\n*   Integer Overflow or Wraparound.\n*   Out-of-bounds Write vulnerabilities in functions like `torch.jit.jit_module_from_flatbuffer`, when using `@torch.jit.script`, and through `torch.lstm_cell`.\n*   Buffer Overflow issues in functions like `unpack_sequence` and `pad_packed_sequence`.\n*   Improper Resource Shutdown or Release through `torch.cuda.nccl.reduce`.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"06275e7a7e88d399\">>>","citations":[{"url":"https://cyberpress.org/pytorch-vulnerability-allows-memory-corruption-leading-to-remote-code-execution/","title":"cyberpress.org"},{"url":"https://security.snyk.io/package/pip/torch/2.9.1","title":"snyk.io"},{"url":"https://security.snyk.io/package/pip/torch","title":"snyk.io"}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774908151726}}
{"type":"message","id":"44012d01","parentId":"4c03ccb9","timestamp":"2026-03-30T22:02:31.740Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"tool_7Alrl1Ta3EoFN0q1UEi5yj9f","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"requests 2.32.0 security vulnerabilities\",\n  \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n  \"model\": \"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n  \"tookMs\": 6202,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"content\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"d62dc624dff3d71f\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nRequests 2.32.0 has several known security vulnerabilities. It is affected by issues that could lead to sensitive information disclosure and bypass of security restrictions.\\n\\nKey vulnerabilities in Requests 2.32.0 include:\\n\\n*   **.netrc Credential Leakage (CVE-2024-47081)**: Releases prior to 2.32.4, including 2.32.0, are vulnerable to a URL parsing issue. A maliciously crafted URL combined with a trusted environment could lead to the leakage of `.netrc` credentials to third parties. This issue was addressed in version 2.32.4. To mitigate this in older versions, the use of the `.netrc` file can be disabled with `trust_env=False` on a Requests Session.\\n*   **Certificate Verification Bypass (CVE-2024-35195)**: In versions prior to 2.32.0, if the first request made through a Requests `Session` used `verify=False` to disable certificate verification, all subsequent requests to the same host would continue to ignore certificate verification, regardless of changes to the `verify` value. This behavior persists for the lifetime of the connection in the connection pool. This vulnerability was fixed in version 2.32.0. However, the initial fix in 2.32.0 was yanked, and the next available fixed version is 2.32.2.\\n*   **SSLContext Caching Issues**: An `SSLContext` caching feature introduced in 2.32.0 created new problems, which led the Requests team to revert this feature due to unsustainable long-term maintenance. This indicates potential instability or unforeseen security implications with this feature in 2.32.0.\\n*   **Insecure Temporary File (CVE-2026-25645)**: While specifically fixed in 2.33.0, the `requests.utils.extract_zipped_paths` function in earlier versions could be vulnerable to unauthorized file replacement if applications directly call it.\\n\\nIt is highly recommended to upgrade to a newer, patched version of the `requests` library (e.g., 2.32.4 or higher) to mitigate these known vulnerabilities.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"d62dc624dff3d71f\\\">>>\",\n  \"citations\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://github.com/opensearch-project/data-prepper/issues/5762\",\n      \"title\": \"github.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/community/updates/\",\n      \"title\": \"readthedocs.io\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://data.safetycli.com/packages/pypi/requests/changelog\",\n      \"title\": \"safetycli.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://my.f5.com/manage/s/article/K000141129\",\n      \"title\": \"f5.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://security.snyk.io/package/pip/requests/2.32.0\",\n      \"title\": \"snyk.io\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"requests 2.32.0 security vulnerabilities","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash","tookMs":6202,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"gemini","wrapped":true},"content":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"d62dc624dff3d71f\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nRequests 2.32.0 has several known security vulnerabilities. It is affected by issues that could lead to sensitive information disclosure and bypass of security restrictions.\n\nKey vulnerabilities in Requests 2.32.0 include:\n\n*   **.netrc Credential Leakage (CVE-2024-47081)**: Releases prior to 2.32.4, including 2.32.0, are vulnerable to a URL parsing issue. A maliciously crafted URL combined with a trusted environment could lead to the leakage of `.netrc` credentials to third parties. This issue was addressed in version 2.32.4. To mitigate this in older versions, the use of the `.netrc` file can be disabled with `trust_env=False` on a Requests Session.\n*   **Certificate Verification Bypass (CVE-2024-35195)**: In versions prior to 2.32.0, if the first request made through a Requests `Session` used `verify=False` to disable certificate verification, all subsequent requests to the same host would continue to ignore certificate verification, regardless of changes to the `verify` value. This behavior persists for the lifetime of the connection in the connection pool. This vulnerability was fixed in version 2.32.0. However, the initial fix in 2.32.0 was yanked, and the next available fixed version is 2.32.2.\n*   **SSLContext Caching Issues**: An `SSLContext` caching feature introduced in 2.32.0 created new problems, which led the Requests team to revert this feature due to unsustainable long-term maintenance. This indicates potential instability or unforeseen security implications with this feature in 2.32.0.\n*   **Insecure Temporary File (CVE-2026-25645)**: While specifically fixed in 2.33.0, the `requests.utils.extract_zipped_paths` function in earlier versions could be vulnerable to unauthorized file replacement if applications directly call it.\n\nIt is highly recommended to upgrade to a newer, patched version of the `requests` library (e.g., 2.32.4 or higher) to mitigate these known vulnerabilities.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"d62dc624dff3d71f\">>>","citations":[{"url":"https://github.com/opensearch-project/data-prepper/issues/5762","title":"github.com"},{"url":"https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/community/updates/","title":"readthedocs.io"},{"url":"https://data.safetycli.com/packages/pypi/requests/changelog","title":"safetycli.com"},{"url":"https://my.f5.com/manage/s/article/K000141129","title":"f5.com"},{"url":"https://security.snyk.io/package/pip/requests/2.32.0","title":"snyk.io"}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774908151732}}
